Principal Component Analysis (PCA)

Overview

Principal Component Analysis (PCA) is a statistical technique used to reduce a set of correlated variables 
into a smaller number of uncorrelated components while preserving as much variation in the data as possible.

Purpose

PCA is primarily used for:
	•	Dimensionality reduction
	•	Data preprocessing before modeling
	•	Handling multicollinearity
	•	Data visualization

Key Concept

PCA creates new variables (principal components) that are weighted combinations of the original variables.
	•	The first component captures the largest amount of variance
	•	Each subsequent component captures progressively less

When to Use PCA

Use PCA when:
	•	You have many correlated variables
	•	You want to simplify your dataset
	•	You are building predictive models
	•	You need to combine multiple measures into a composite index

Important Considerations
	•	Variables should be correlated
	•	Data should be standardized if variables are on different scales
	•	PCA is data-driven and does not model underlying constructs

Interpretation

Principal components represent shared variance across variables, not theoretical constructs. 
Results should be interpreted as data summaries rather than latent variables.

Example Use Case

In health outcomes research, PCA can be used to combine patient-reported outcomes (e.g., PROMIS), 
cognitive performance scores, and financial toxicity measures into a single composite index representing overall patient burden.
